his support created opportunities for American physicians and medical trainees to interact with local practitioners, treat patients, and shape health policy in Botswana.While global health has emerged as a powerful call to planetary moral action, the nature of this exhortation remains unclear. Is global health a new movement for social justice, or is it neocolonial, creating new dependencies under the banner of humanitarianism? Betsey B. Brada shows that global health is a frontier, an imaginative framework that organizes the space, time, and ethics of encounter. Learning to Save the World reveals how individuals and collectivities engaged in global health—visiting experts as well as local clinicians and patients—come to regard themselves and others in terms of this framework.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh  aglobal health pedagogies, botswana HIV treatment anthropology, botswana medical anthropology, botswana HIV.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023 Englishz978311131921608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023z9783111318615oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501762444?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501762444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501762444/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete 